      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 4.1 Logic"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "9d093554",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Pricing Logic:"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "c2d51310",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Market Making Logic: \n",
        "\n",
        "Base spread: FV +- .01 = .02. FV: Fair Value\n",
        "\n",
        "The spread changes based off VIX & Current Inventory (Position Size):\n",
        "\n",
        "VIX - For every point of VIX, the spread increases by .001. Ie. VIX = 20 -> spread increases by .02\n",
        "\n",
        "Inventory - For every (Kalshi) contract in our inventory, the spread increases by .00025. Ie. 80 Contracts Held -> spread increases by .02\n",
        "\n",
        "Outside of regular market hours (9:30 AM - 4:00 PM EST), the spread increases by .10 to account for the significantly lower liquidity & trade volume.\n",
        "\n",
        "The spread midpoint is skewed away from the fair by (-).0005 * Kalshi Contract Position. Ie. Holding 40 \"Yes\" Contracts -> fair decreases by .02. This is done to reduce our axed position faster.\n",
        "\n",
        "Finally, we build in Kalshi Maker Fees into our spread.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Kalshi Maker Fees: fee = round up(0.0175 * C * P * (1 - P)), \n",
        "where P = price, C = number of contracts.\n",
        "\n",
        "Our bids & offers are placed on the end of our spread.\n",
        "\n",
        "We also manage our bid / ask size based on inventory (total & sided) to stay within the following parameters:\n",
        "- Default Quote Size = 50\n",
        "- Max Quote Size = 100\n",
        "- Max Abs Inventory for Size = 500"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "a7c4984d",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Simulation Logic:\n",
        "\n",
        "The simulation seeks to mimic Kalshi taker trades. We assume last in queue position at our bid/ask prices. All of our data gets passed every second, so our simulation iterates through each second of our data. On each tick:\n",
        "- We update our quote for each contract.\n",
        "- Check for fills (bid_taken < our bid or ask_taken > our ask)\n",
        "- Contracts resolve to be worth either 0 or $1 depending on outcome at expry."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "06311307",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Delta Hedging Logic"
      ]
    },
